Northampton County in current day Northampton County, North Carolina was formed in 1741 when Bertie County was divided and it was first inhabited by the Meherrin Indians and was settled by English colonizers about 1712. The county was created in 1741 from Bertie County and it was named for James Compton, 5th Earl of Northampton. In 1759 parts of Northampton County, Bertie County, and Chowan County were combined to form Hertford County, from 1741 to 1779 the county seat was located on a 50-acre tract near an Indian settlement called Malintocque by the courthouse was constructed there. This courthouse was burned by Confederate troops in 1862 during the Civil War, in 1759 the Read House Historic Site was built in the plantation country south of Jackson.
